<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06087198 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06087198 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  US; MILITARY; LEADER; RELATION; PRESIDENT; MIDEAST; WAR  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf says that he recommended to President Bush last monthto &quot;continue the march&quot; into Iraq to annihilate Iraq's armed forces but thatas a result of the Feb. 27 cease-fire ordered by Bush, significant elements ofIraq's army and Republican Guard escaped across the Euphrates River and intoBasra.;    Intelligence officials say those forces have been engaged in acampaign of repression and atrocities against the insurrection in Iraq.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  SCHWARZKOPF HINTS TRUCE WAS PREMATURE  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     In an apparent effort to stifle any idea that there had been disagreementamong top administration and military leaders, Defense Secretary Dick Cheneysaid today that Schwarzkopf had raised &quot;no objection&quot; to ending the war.;   Cheney said Bush's decision &quot;was based on the recommendations of his seniormilitary advisers&quot; and &quot;was coordinated with and concurred in&quot; bySchwarzkopf.;    &quot;General Schwarzkopf and (chairman of the Joint Chiefs ofStaff) General Powell were consulted and made the recommendation to me and tothe president that we had achieved our military objectives and agreed that itwas time to end the campaign,&quot; Cheney's statement said.;    In a televisioninterview with David Frost, Schwarzkopf called Bush's decision &quot;courageous,&quot;but also said historians would probably review the decision for years tocome.;    The general said the allied forces had the Iraqis &quot;in a rout&quot; andcould have continued to rain great destruction on them.;    But thepresident's decision to halt the war &quot;did leave some escape routes open forthem to get back out,&quot; he said.;    Had the war gone on for another 24 hours,he said, &quot;we could have inflicted terrible damage on them.&quot;;    When theshooting stopped, the general said, he was &quot;suckered&quot; by Iraqi militarycommanders who asked for and received permission to fly helicopters over Iraq,ostensibly for transporting key officials between cities.;    But instead, hesaid, the Iraqis have sent their helicopter gunships aloft to assaultinsurgent forces seeking to overthrow President Saddam Hussein.;   Schwarzkopf also accused the Cable News Network of &quot;aiding and abetting&quot; theIraqis by picking up Iraqi television broadcasts of captured U.S. and Britishpilots.;    &quot;I did resent CNN aiding and abetting an enemy who was violatingthe Geneva convention,&quot; he said.;    The general went on to say he understoodthere was a First Amendment protecting the &quot;public's right to know.&quot;;    &quot;Ijust think that in the future when people choose to justify their actionsbased upon the American public's right to know, they'd better check with theAmerican public first because the American public has made it very clear to me. . . how they felt about the term 'the American people's right to know' as itwas being used by the people who were doing that sort of thing.&quot;;    StevenHaworth, a spokesman for CNN in Atlanta, replied: &quot;I think there were somefamilies who might differ with General Schwarzkopf and were relieved to seethat their loved ones were in dangerous situations but at least alive.&quot;;  IFYOU'RE INTERESTED; The interview will be broadcast at; 8 p.m. today onKQED-TV, Ch. 9.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Washington  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910327  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  504  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday March 27, 199100087198,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  <